lay layer rather than the core feature.\n\nNow let me pull together the full test results and document my findings. The `status` command auto-detects single instances and shows helpful disambiguation when multiple exist. `approve_gate.py` correctly reads from instance-specific directories and errors appropriately when the instance flag is missing. The old flat `state.json` remains untouched with no migration needed, and instance directories are properly gitignored.\n\nThere's one failing criterion — `status.py` doesn't display config values. I'm considering whether this is a genuine bug or just a test limitation, since the config layering itself works correctly. I should probably file a P2 ticket for this, and I'm thinking TICKET-0257 based on the existing numbering convention. The workaround of manually inspecting config via Python confirms this is P2 severity. Now I need to figure out whether displaying config in `status.py` was actually part of the implementation scope or if it's a gap in the acceptance criteria itself — the criterion explicitly requires it, but checking the related tickets might show it wasn't assigned to any implementation work. The `_print_full_status` function displays instance metadata like cost, active workers, completed waves, retries, and pending gates, but nowhere does it actually output the config values—so the requirement definitely isn't met. I'll file this as a P2 bug assigned to systems-programmer and then check which tickets touched status.py to understand the original scope.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1263,"cache_read_input_tokens":51900,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1263},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"36142e0f-0ce3-4c03-9bff-d9ba36b531fa","uuid":"20f25cd1-06d8-49ee-8bdc-b89ab36e8e0e"},{"